The '''[[1984 NFL season|1984]] [[St. Louis Rams|Los Angeles Rams]] season''' was the team's 47th year with the [[National Football League]] and the 39th season in [[Los Angeles]]. During this season second-year running back [[Eric Dickerson]] set the NFL record for most rushing yards in a season, with 2,105 yards.
==Offseason== ===NFL Draft=== {{Main|1984 NFL Draft}} {| class="wikitable sortable sortable" ! style="background:#14345B;color:#ffc322;" width="7%"| Round ! style="background:#14345B;color:#ffc322;" width="7%"| Pick ! style="background:#14345B;color:#ffc322;" width="20%"| Player ! style="background:#14345B;color:#ffc322;" width="15%"| Position ! style="background:#14345B;color:#ffc322;" width="20%"| School/Club Team |- |}
==Regular season== ===Eric Dickerson=== In his second season, Dickerson continued his onslaught of the NFL record book. As a rookie, Dickerson established rookie records for most rushing attempts (390), most rushing yards gained (1,808) and most touchdowns rushing (18), including another two receiving touchdowns.<ref name="ericdickerson29.com">Eric's Days as a Ram, http://www.ericdickerson29.com/rams.htm</ref> His efforts earned him All-Pro, [[Pro Bowl]], Player of the Year and [[NFL Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] honors.<ref>Eric Dickerson: Pro Football Hall of Fame, http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?PLAYER_ID=55</ref>
Eleven times during the 1984 season, he gained more than 100 yards rushing, breaking the record of 100-yard games in a season held by [[O.J. Simpson]]. His 2,105 total yards rushing in the 1984 NFL season beat Simpsonâs 1973 NFL season record of 2,003 yards rushing in a single season. To date, no one has rushed for more yards in a single [[NFL]] season. However, Simpson's career high rushing total came in a 14 game season, whereas Dickerson's mark was set during a 16-game season.<ref name="ericdickerson29.com"/> Dickerson broke OJ's record with a 215-yard performance in a 27-16 Rams win over the [[Houston Oilers]], Week 15 of the season.
